We recommended that the Municipal Mayor and the HRMO to:
Come up with a concrete policy guideline relative to the hiring and rehiring of JO personnel to establish a clear expectation and protect the rights of both the employees and the Municipality;
Provide Statement of Duties and Responsibilities of JO personnel to clearly identify their responsibilities and perform their duties efficiently;
Set a standard wage rate based on their qualifications and suitability for the job applied, subject to the Municipality’s financial capacity; and
Install a biometrics system for JO personnel to properly monitor their DTRs;
We further recommended that the Municipal Mayor/Vice Mayor or their authorized representative provide a written justification for the 170 Job Orders that were absent during the headcount along with a valid document and identification proving their existence.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor: 
create an Inventory Committee to complete the physical inventory of properties for the One-Time Cleansing of PPE Account Balances;

direct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal GSO to a) regularly update the PPELCs and Property Cards, respectively; and b) reconcile both records to determine the cause/s of the variance for proper disposition thereof.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require:
the OIC-Municipal Accountant to:

prepare and submit BRS within ten (10) days after the end of each month;

take up in the books unrecorded reconciling items like the interest income and those which have been long outstanding;

prepare adjusting journal entries to restore the liabilities of the Municipality to those creditors whose checks became stale and cancelled to reflect the correct Cash in Bank balance.

the Municipal Treasurer to review the stale checks and secure the addresses of the payees for notification of the return of stale checks in their possession for replacement.

We recommended that the LCE require the Municipal Accountant and the AOs concerned the following:
a) The concerned AOs to liquidate immediately their outstanding cash advances as required under Sec. 89 of P. D. 1445 and COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;
b) Management should refrain from granting additional cash advances unless the liquidation of the previous cash advance from the AO concerned is submitted, or if not, a proper accounting is made thereof;
c) Prepare a Subsidiary Ledger per AO to properly monitor grant and liquidation of cash advances.

We recommended that:
a. Monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF should be prepared and certified correct by the Accountant and submit to the COA Auditor on or before the 15th day after the end of each month;
b. The Municipal Budget Officer maintain a separate Registry of Appropriations, Allotments and Obligations (RAAO) for the LDRRMF such as RAAO - for QRF, RAAO - for MOOE, and RAAO - for CO;
c. Require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to facilitate the transfer of unexpended balance of QRF and MOOE of the LDRRMF for the year 2016.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to:
a. Update the reconciliation of the bank balances so that all reconciling items can be properly/accurately accounted for;
b. Regularly prepare monthly reconciliation statement for all trust fund accounts.

We recommended that Local Chief Executive require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to:
a. Maintain an updated lapsing schedule or Depreciation Schedule for all its Properties and Equipment in order to regularly provide for the depreciation allowance for the current year;
b. To provide adjusting entries in the government equity to reflect the depreciation expense for Infrastructure Assets, Buildings and Structures, Machinery and Other PPEs for the calendar year 2019.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to:

a.	Update the reconciliation of the bank balances so that so that all reconciling items can be properly/accurately accounted for;
b.	Regularly prepare monthly reconciliation statement for all trust fund accounts.

1.7 In view of the noted lapses, we have recommended that-
 Management create an Inventory Committee that will conduct
comprehensive annual physical count of PPE of the LGU;
 Inventory Committee prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Property,
Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) properly reconciled with the PPE records
of the GSO and Municipal Accountant, and submit the same to COA not later
than January 31 of the ensuing year;
 Municipal Accountant and General Services Officer maintain PPE Ledger
Cards and Property Cards for easy reconciliation of the account;
 General Services Officer maintain ARE/PAR and ensure its renewal every
three years; and
 Municipal Accountant to effect necessary adjusting entries for variances
noted, if any, to establish the accuracy of the reported balance of the PPE;

We recommended that the LCE direct the:
MDRRMO and the budget office to stop charging LDRRMF beyond the available appropriation;
MDRRMO, in coordination with the Municipal Development Council, to prepare supplemental investment plans (in case of re-alignment or changes in the original budget) in order to strictly monitor the proper utilization of the LDRRMF;
Budget Officer to maintain RAAO on the LDRRMF; And,
The Municipal Accountant to regularly update its recording of the LDRRMF obligations and/or disbursements in its subsidiary ledgers in order to certify the Monthly Sources and Utilization Reports prepared by the MDRRMO.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
• Inventory Committee to coordinate with the Municipal Engineer to use the road network map of the Municipality to facilitate the preparation of a proper inventory and reporting of the Municipality’s road network system;
• Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;
• Municipal Treasurer to maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Cards for all roads and its components; and
• Municipal Accountant to record the amount of road networks required in the transitory provision of COA Circular No. 2015-008 for the fair presentation of the Property, Plant and Equipment account in the financial statements.

We recommended that Local Chief Executive to require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to:
a. Keep and maintain subsidiary records and appropriate Road Network Property Ledger Cards (Annex D) for ALL roads and road components for every road network;
b. To stop the allowance of five (5%) percent residual value for depreciable component of road networks in the computation of depreciation expenses and/or accumulated depreciation;
c. provide appropriate disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements (FS) on Road Network System using the format in Annex B;

We recommended that Local Chief Executive to require the General Services Officer to:
a.	Maintain a complete Road Network Property Cards for ALL roads and road components for every road network;
b.	Maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map;
c.	Reconcile discrepancies of the Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network and the total amounts in the Local Road Network Property Cards.

We recommended the:
1. LCE, in coordination with the MBO, to make proper planning in the preparation of the Annual Budget in order to avoid unforeseen contingency of all budgetary items and consequently resorting to illegal transfers of savings;

2. Sangguniang Bayan to adhere strictly to existing rules, laws and regulations in the use of appropriated funds and savings;

We recommended the Local Chief Executive to direct:

1. The Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) require the complete documentation of the bidder’s requirements such as PhilGEPS Registration Number , Mayor’s/Business Permits, Income & Business Tax Returns and Omnibus Sworn Statements, as applicable before entering a contract and engaging the services of the prospective suppliers in compliance with Section 54.6, Annex H/Appendix A of 2016 RIRR;

2. The BAC to maintain an updated file and database of bidder’s above-mentioned requirements.

3. The BAC to follow the guidelines under Section 54.2 and 54.3 prescribed by the 2016 Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations of RA 9184 related to the posting requirements of the LGUs procurement activities;

We recommended that the LCE direct the:

1. OIC-MPDC to identify carefully the projects to be included in the AIP and make sure proper consultations from the constituents were made in order to make sure that same will be beneficial to them;
2. OIC-Municipal Engineer to monitor regularly all infrastructure projects to avoid delayed implementations;
3. OIC-MBO to adjust obligated amount for the project as of year-end, deducting the liquidated damages on delayed implementation; and,
4.        OIC-Municipal Accountant to provide for the liquidated damages to be deducted from the claim of the contractor

We recommended that Local Chief Executive to require:
a. The Municipal General Services Officer to maintain a complete and properly accomplished Report of the Physical Inventory of the Property, Plant and Equipment and updated Property Cards as prescribed by Section 119 & 124 of COA Circular 2002-003;

b. The Municipal Accountant to maintain a complete and properly accomplished Property, Plant & Equipment Ledger Cards, Real Property Ledger Cards as prescribed by Section 119 & 120 of COA Circular 2002-003;
(c) the reconciliation of the record of the GSO and the Municipal Accountant to address the material amount of discrepancy of PEE per physical count and that of PPE in the books.

W e have recommended that
management:
a . Instruct the Project Facilitator to submit a justification for certifying the project as 100 percent projects and request since 2020.
b . require the concerned contractor to employ corrective measures on the stone masonry and concrete curb and gutter. Otherwise, demand the refund of the cost of the deficiencies;
c . conduct inspection of the project upon notice of the contractor that said deficiency was rectified to determine whether corrective measures were satisfactorily made;
d . submit request for re-inspection of the rectified project to the Auditor for appropriate action.

We have recommended that management ensure that unexpended/
unobligated funds from prior years LDRRM are treated as Trust Liability at
the end of the year and duly transferred to a special trust fund account;

We have recommended the following:
.  
That management through the Municipal Accountant submit the SB authorization/resolution, contract of services/job orders, certification of the LCE/Personnel Officer on the necessity of hiring job orders, accomplishment reports and duly accomplished Daily Time Records as required under the aforementioned regulations;

That management submit the required documents for evaluation as to the legality, regularity and propriety of the payments made for repairs and maintenance of motor vehicles and other equipment as well as the duly accomplished Driver’s Trip Tickets to support the expenditures for fuel, oil and lubricants;

That the use of government vehicles be supported with properly accomplished Driver’s Trip Tickets which shall be serially numbered, a summary of which shall be made at the end of the month in the Monthly Report of Official Travels.  A copy of this report should be submitted monthly to the audit team as required under COA Circular No. 77-61. Moreover, a list of municipal vehicles and other equipment and its accomplishment report should also be furnished to the audit team for verification purposes;

That management maintain records of repair for each heavy equipment and motor vehicle to determine the frequency of the repairs made.  Consider disposing all vehicles and equipment which are already beyond economical repair in order to cut costs on repairs and maintenance; and

That henceforth, the Municipal Accountant and Treasurer should verify the attached supporting documents before payments are made

We have  recommended the following;

That management ensure the immediate completion of the on-going projects which have already incurred significant delays;
Include unworkable days in estimating the number of days to complete a project to come up with a realistic project duration so as to avoid delays and the consequent imposition of liquidated damages; and
Require the Municipal Engineer to conduct regular monitoring and supervision of projects to ensure that infrastructure projects are accomplished in accordance with the terms of the contract and to document the same and to impose liquidated damages and other appropriate sanctions, as maybe justified.

We have recommended the following:

that management submit a copy of the duly approved APP that includes procurement for goods and infrastructure projects. Henceforth, an APP should be prepared and approved before undertaking any procurement and should be duly submitted for review and verification;

that management submit the missing documentations as stated in the foregoing discussions.  Henceforth, complete bidding documents should be submitted on time for COA evaluation and review;

that the BAC observe the required pre-procurement conference for infrastructure project with an ABC above ₱5 million to ensure, among others, that the procurement is in accordance with the project and annual procurement plans and to determine the readiness of the agency for the procurement at hand;

that the BAC, through its BAC Secretariat, observe the proper advertising and posting of the Invitation to Bid as prescribed in the Revised IRR of RA 9184 to encourage more participants in the bidding process and intensify the competition among them, which in turn, will ensure that the LGU will get the best possible proposals, as to quality and cost, for the project sought to be procured. The Municipality should have a specific prominent and public place reserved for posting of the Invitation to Bid such as bulletin board in the municipal hall;

that the BAC invites at least three (3) observers to attend in all stages of the procurement process to promote transparency and ensure that bidding is existent in the procurement activities of the agency as provided in Section 13 of the Revised IRR of RA 9184;

that the Municipality ensure that all the documentary requirements are complied with before entering into contract with the winning bidder;

that the BAC, through the BAC Secretariat, shall post the Notice of Award and Notice to Proceed in the PhilGEPS to promote transparency and efficiency in the conduct of procurement procedures; and

that the BAC should strictly comply with the provisions of RA 9184 in the conduct of public bidding and awarding of contracts/projects. BAC members, BAC secretariat and the TWG should familiarize themselves with the different rules and regulations set forth by RA 9184. Clear and readable documents and lacking documents should be submitted for COA evaluation and review.

To exert all available remedies provided by laws and regulations in enforcing the immediate settlement of the outstanding receivables;
to retrace prior year transactions to ascertain the details of receivables with unknown nature; and
For dormant receivables, a request for authority to write off together with documents to justify the request may be submitted for evaluation and proper action in accordance with the COA Circular No.2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

15.9 In view of the noted observations, we have recommended the following:
the MPDC lead the setting up and maintenance of GAD database to serve as basis for gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation;
the GAD GFPS prepare the GPB through the application of the HGDG and submit the same to the PPDO for DILG review and approval;
the GAD GFPS follow the prescribed format of GPB and GAD AR; and
that the GAD Focal Point identify programs, projects and activities that address gender issues such as promotion of gender-responsive governance, protection and fulfillment of women’s human rights and promotion of women’s economic empowerment to be included in the GAD Plan.

We reiterated our recommendation that - 
The Municipal Government create an Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of PPE in the Municipality. To facilitate the inventory taking, all department heads are advised to instruct their members to cooperate in the conduct of physical count;  

the Inventory Committee prepare the Physical Inventory Reports to be submitted to the Property Officer for verification and reconciliation with the records maintained by the Accounting Office and the property cards of the Property Unit;

the Municipal Government conduct a proper disposal of unserviceable property; and

henceforth, the Accounting Office prepare and maintain PPELC as required under regulations to facilitate reconciliation with the Property Office.

